{%- assign accent_color = '#C4520A' -%}
{%- assign dark_color = '#141836' -%}
{%- capture faq_rows -%}
ordering##ordering-1##What material should I use for patches?##The best material for <strong>custom patches</strong> is <strong>twill fabric</strong> for embroidery, <strong>polyester</strong> for printed patches, and <strong>felt</strong> for handmade options. These offer durability, clean stitching, and excellent color retention.
ordering##ordering-2##How do I print a patch?##<strong>Printed custom patches</strong> are made using <strong>dye-sublimation printing</strong> on polyester. The design is heat-transferred and finished with an iron-on, Velcro, or sew-on backing for easy application.
ordering##ordering-3##What is the customs code for embroidered patch?##The international customs code for <strong>embroidered patches</strong> is typically <strong>HS Code 5810.92.10</strong>. Always verify with your local customs authority for accuracy.
ordering##ordering-4##What stabilizer to use for making patches?##Use a <strong>cut-away</strong> or <strong>tear-away stabilizer</strong> when making <strong>embroidered patches</strong>. It keeps the design crisp and prevents puckering during dense stitching.
shipping##shipping-1##How do I make my own patches?##To create <strong>custom patches</strong> at home:<ol><li>Choose fabric and stabilizer</li><li>Digitize your design</li><li>Use an embroidery machine or hand embroidery</li><li>Finish with an <strong>iron-on, Velcro,</strong> or <strong>sew-on backing</strong></li></ol>
shipping##shipping-2##What material can you not iron-on patches?##Avoid using <strong>iron-on patches</strong> on <strong>leather, nylon, silk</strong>, or waterproof materials. These fabrics cannot handle the heat or do not allow proper adhesion.
shipping##shipping-3##What machine do I need to make patches?##A <strong>multi-needle embroidery machine</strong>, like Brother or Tajima, is best for <strong>professional custom patch production</strong>. Entry-level machines also work for hobbyists.
payment##payment-1##Can I get a patch made from a picture?##Yes, you can turn a <strong>photo into a custom patch</strong> by converting the image into a digital embroidery file or printing it via sublimation.
payment##payment-2##What is the difference between printed and embroidered patches?##<strong>Embroidered patches</strong> are stitched for texture and durability, while <strong>printed patches</strong> use ink for detailed, high-resolution designs. Choose based on your branding needs.
payment##payment-3##How do you avoid copyright with embroidery?##To avoid copyright issues with embroidery:<ol><li>Avoid using copyrighted logos or images in <strong>custom patch designs</strong></li><li>Use original artwork</li><li>Get licensing permission to stay compliant</li></ol>
product##product-1##Does Custom Ink do patches?##<strong>Custom Ink</strong> offers limited <strong>custom patch options</strong>. For full control, quality, and branding flexibility, choose a specialist like <strong>Yak Patches</strong>.
product##product-2##Are patches considered embroidery?##Yes, most <strong>custom patches</strong>, especially embroidered ones, are a form of <strong>decorative embroidery</strong>, stitched onto fabric and finished with a backing.
product##product-3##What can I use instead of stabilizers?##Alternatives to stabilizers include:<ol><li><strong>Felt</strong></li><li><strong>Interfacing</strong></li><li>Double layers of thick fabric</li></ol>However, true <strong>custom patches</strong> require stabilizers for best results.
product##product-4##What is the difference between stabilizer and interfacing in embroidery?##<strong>Stabilizers</strong> are temporary and support the design during stitching. <strong>Interfacing</strong> is permanent and adds structure to the fabric after stitching.
returns##returns-1##What is the best sewing technique for patches?##The best sewing techniques for patches are:<ol><li><strong>Satin stitch</strong> - protects edges from fraying</li><li><strong>Zig-zag stitch</strong> - provides secure attachment</li></ol>Both techniques give a clean, professional finish to <strong>custom patches</strong>.
returns##returns-2##How to turn hand embroidery into a patch?##To turn hand embroidery into a patch:<ol><li>Embroider your design on fabric with a stabilizer</li><li>Trim the patch to desired shape</li><li>Add a backing</li></ol>This converts handwork into a functional <strong>custom patch</strong>.
returns##returns-3##Does Hobby Lobby make patches?##<strong>Hobby Lobby</strong> sells pre-made <strong>iron-on patches</strong> and embroidery kits but does not offer <strong>custom patch manufacturing</strong>.
custom##custom-1##How do I start using patches?##To start using patches:<ol><li>Select your <strong>custom patch type</strong> - embroidered, woven, or printed</li><li>Choose an application method: iron-on, sewing, or Velcro</li><li>Apply it to your item depending on your use case</li></ol>
custom##custom-2##Is it better to iron or sew on patches?##<strong>Sew-on patches</strong> are more permanent and durable, especially on washable fabrics. <strong>Iron-on patches</strong> are faster but may peel over time.
custom##custom-3##Why isn't my iron-on patch sticking?##If your <strong>iron-on patch</strong> does not stick, check these common issues:<ol><li>The fabric might be incompatible</li><li>The iron may be too cool</li><li>You are not applying enough pressure</li></ol>
custom##custom-4##What fabric is best for patches?##<strong>Twill</strong> is the most commonly used fabric for <strong>embroidered patches</strong>. <strong>Polyester</strong> works best for printed patches due to its ink absorption.
custom##custom-5##What stabilizer to use for patches?##A <strong>heavy-duty cut-away stabilizer</strong> is ideal for <strong>embroidered custom patches</strong>, especially on complex or high-density designs.
custom##custom-6##Can I use a sewing machine for patches?##Yes, a <strong>sewing machine</strong> works well for attaching <strong>custom patches</strong> using zig-zag or straight stitches, depending on your fabric and finish.
custom##custom-7##What needle do you use for patches?##Use a <strong>sharp embroidery needle</strong>, size <strong>75/11</strong> or <strong>80/12</strong>, for most <strong>custom patches</strong>. For thick fabrics, a <strong>90/14</strong> needle is better.
custom##custom-8##How long does it take to create a patch?##Creating one <strong>custom patch</strong> takes 15-60 minutes, depending on design complexity. Bulk orders may take 3-7 business days.
custom##custom-9##Can I take my patch off to shower?##<strong>Iron-on patches</strong> are not waterproof. Use <strong>Velcro patches</strong> if you need to remove them for showers or washing.
custom##custom-10##Can you put patches without sewing?##Yes, you can attach patches without sewing using these methods:<ol><li><strong>Iron-on patches</strong></li><li><strong>Heat-seal patches</strong></li><li><strong>Adhesive custom patches</strong></li></ol>However, sewing offers the best long-term durability.
custom##custom-11##What are the three types of patches?##The main types of <strong>custom patches</strong> are:<ol><li><strong>Embroidered patches</strong></li><li><strong>Woven patches</strong></li><li><strong>Printed patches</strong></li></ol>
custom##custom-12##Are patches cheaper than embroidery?##Yes, ordering <strong>custom patches</strong> in bulk is usually more cost-effective than direct embroidery on each garment, and allows flexibility in placement.
custom##custom-13##What is a bullion patch?##A <strong>bullion patch</strong> is a high-end <strong>custom patch</strong> made from coiled gold or silver thread. Often handmade, it is used for uniforms or ceremonial garments.
custom##custom-14##Can you sell Disney embroidery?##No, selling <strong>Disney-themed patches</strong> without a license is illegal. It violates both copyright and trademark laws.
custom##custom-15##How do artists avoid copyright infringement?##Artists avoid copyright infringement through these methods:<ol><li>Create <strong>original custom patch designs</strong></li><li>Use content from the public domain</li><li>License existing artwork legally</li></ol>
custom##custom-16##Is it illegal to embroider logos?##Yes, using <strong>trademarked logos</strong> in <strong>custom patches</strong> without permission is a legal violation. Always get authorization or use your own branding.
{%- endcapture -%}
